post_text: Our Titans are all doing a great job of wearing their masks in school. Being that it is the weekend after a few weeks of school, I just want to remind everyone to make sure they are washing their masks frequently. It is best to wash the mask after 1 day of use in the hottest water that is appropriate using soap. There has been evidence that some people can get skin irritations due to wearing masks. Washing the mask frequently and changing it if it becomes wet can help reduce the skin irritations. I appreciate all of our community support with the masks. We had a wonderful quilting group make the blue and gray masks for our students. Our parents have also been supportive in following this new policy. Thank you for your continued support in keeping HTRS Titans healthy and in session.

Elementary students will be assigned laptops in their classrooms by their teachers. Thank you.

Local Regional Writer Winners

Mrs. Bowen is proud to announce the top three Patriot‚Äôs Pen essay winners for this region. All winners are eighth-graders at HTRS. The theme this year was, ‚ÄúWhat Makes America Great?‚Äù Normally there would be a presentation of the awards at the HTRS eighth-grade promotional night.

The first place winner is KayLee Jeralds. KayLee lives in Humboldt. Her parents are Amber Newman and Charlie Liberty.

Second place winner is Avery Dierberger. Avery lives in Table Rock. Her parents are Todd and Samantha Dierberger.

Third place winner goes to MaeLynn Bittner. Her parents are Jeremy and Gina Bittner from Dawson.

All three girls were awarded a monetary gift, certificate, and a very nice medal. The Dalton McHugh VFW Auxiliary out of Pawnee City reaches out to the school every year for participation, and it is so appreciated. Thanks to all of the students that submitted their essays this year.

post_text: SENIOR ALERT The Richardson County Clerk‚Äôs Office has always made plans for each election year to come to the High School and have a voter registration event for the Seniors. With the unfortunate circumstances this year we were unable to do that. We do want you to know that you still have time to REGISTER TO VOTE. Any student, Senior or Junior who will be 18 on or before Tuesday, November 3, 2020 is eligible to register to vote now and vote in the Primary Election. You can click on this link https://co.richardson.ne.us/pdfs/election/2020/Voter%20Registration%20Form%20Fillable.pdf and fill out your registration form, print and then sign and deliver to the drop box located on the north lower level entrance (18th Street) of the Richardson County Courthouse by 6:00 p.m. on Friday, May 1. If you have questions please call the Richardson County Clerk at 402-245-2911.

post_text:
The Nebraska Schools Activities Association has made the following decision:

Sports Physicals on file for the 2019 - 2020 school year for current students enrolled in grades 9 - 11 will now be valid for the 2020 - 2021 school year. All incoming freshman (current 8th graders) planning on participating in athletics will still be required to provide sports physical paperwork dated no earlier than May 1, 2020.

All students entering 7th grade (current 6th graders) will be required to provide sports physical paperwork. This is a Nebraska Department of Education law and is required of all 7th graders.

Physicals on file for students entering 8th grade (current 7th graders) will be valid for the 2020 - 2021 school year.

To clarify, only students entering 7th and 9th grades next year will need to get physicals for 2020 - 2021

post_text:
COVID-19 NEWS UPDATE

To effectively address the COVID-19 outbreak, HTRS is doing everything possible
to keep our students and staff healthy. It is our goal to keep our school open unless
the State of Nebraska government agencies issue a mandatory closure. However, to
address health concerns, we will be implementing the following guidelines.
‚Ä¢ All vendors and delivery persons will be screened by our school nurse before entering the building.
‚Ä¢ Parent drop off and pick up will happen outside the main entrance. HTRS staff
will be present to assist in this process.
‚Ä¢ The Fitness Center will be closed to the public until further notice.

HTRS has implemented these guidelines and will continually evaluate and communicate
updates. We want to be proactive rather than reactive when it comes to the safety
of each of our communities and those at risk. We appreciate your understanding and
helping with our mission.

Sherri L. Edmundson

Sherri L. Edmundson
Superintendent

post_text: High School Robotics class built towers out of paper towel rolls. The challenge was to build at least a 1 foot tower that could support an egg for 1 minute. We tested 5 towers, 3 were successful on the 1st try, another needed a redesign because the tube was too large and egg fell through. The final tower, which was the tallest, tipped over at the 57 second mark.

Good afternoon!

I am writing to ask ALL OF YOU to go nominate our school for the Small Towns Matter campaign through the Ol Red 99.5 radio station.

If we are selected, we WIN bike helmets for EVERY student PLUS $5,000 for our school!!! Can you imagine how awesome that would be?!?

All you have to do is click on this link https://www.newschannelnebraska.com/story/41632940/small-towns-matter-school-giveaway

It asks for a tiny bit of basic information and also "Why should your school win?"

Thank you in advance for taking 2 minutes to do this. I truly think our students would be over the moon excited if were to win!!

Happy Saturday!

Ashlee Meyer

post_text: We have had quite a few students affected by Influenza B this week. Also it may be a good weekend to wash kids belongings, such as coats, backpacks, gloves, and water bottles.

Shoutout from coach Tomek:

If you've been keeping up with the HTRS Lady Titans basketball, you may know we've been having a decent season. So right now I want to give a huge shoutout to a few of our girls.

Katilyn Glathar is sitting 4th in the state (out of ALL classes, A-D2) for Double Doubles, and 7th for Rebounds

Carissa Allen in sitting 7th for Double Doubles and 18th for rebounds

To give you an idea of what the means, Husker Volleyball Recruit Kalyn Meyers from Superior is #1 in both areas, and we're 4th and 7th out of the entire state.

These girls are doing amazing, and couldn't do it without their teammates behind them.
We still have a lot of the season ahead of us so come cheer us on!!

#TitanPride

post_text:
Attention Titans! Bobby Truhe from the KSB law firm in Lincoln will be here on Thursday, January 9th to present to all students in grades 4-12 about digital citizenship. These presentations are open to the public and would be extremely beneficial for parents of teens and pre-teens that have access to social media apps, and online games. If you want the latest information about what is happening in the social media world this presentation is well worth your time. Please join us!

Bobby will present to grades 4-7 at 9:00 a.m. and then present to grades 8-12 at 10:00 each presentation will last about one hour and will be held in the old gym. He is a very engaging presenter and is willing to answer any questions that you might have about keeping your kids safe and responsible users of social media.

We look forward to seeing you on Thursday, January 9th.

#TitanPride

post_text:
Titan Parents please monitor what your children are doing on their phones and electronic devices. We need your help. Our focus this year is being kind to one another and there are some mean things going on this weekend. The HTRS staff cares deeply for all of our students and unfortunately the result of these behaviors get brought back to our environment after the weekend. This damages the positive climate that we have been working so hard on.

The best advice we can give to parents is to block those that are engaging in this type of harassment. However, sometimes parents don‚Äôt always know what is going on.

Every year we have a speaker come in to talk about using social media responsibly and how to use it to build one another up instead of tear each other down. It seems when the weather changes there are more reports of this.

HTRS does have resource officer Lyle McMann who spends a day or two a week with us at school and he has also had some informal conversations with kids on this topic. Please let us know how we can help.

#BeKind #TitanPride

post_text:
The HTRS VB team is continuing their quest and will play Humphrey/Lindsay Holy Family at 3:00 p.m. at Crete high school on Saturday. The pep band/cheerleader bus will depart from school at 12:45 p.m. We are currently organizing an additional bus for students that are not in band that would like to attend. Community members are certainly welcome to ride the bus if there is room on a first come first serve basis after students have signed up. If you are a community member and have interest in riding the pep bus please contact secretary Brittany Freeman and we will add your name to the list. Please give her your phone number so that we can confirm your spot. We will let you know this afternoon (Thursday, October 31st) 402-862-2151
#TitanPride #GoTitans

post_text: Calling all music lovers! HTRS is hosting the Pioneer Conference Vocal Clinic Monday, November 11th. The HTRS Chorus will be joined by the choirs from Johnson Brock, Diller Odell, Falls City Sacred Heart, Lewiston, Lourdes and Pawnee City for an afternoon of rehearsing with our clinician Mr. Brian Johnson from Papio South. There will be a public concert at 7pm to finish our day. HTRS Chorus members will be dismissed early to eat. I hope you will make plans to attend the concert!
